		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=276178"><span id=Scholar>Dothammer</span></a><b><span id=Scholar><br>Scholar</span></b><br /><img alt="Avatar" height="70" width="70" src="/uf/Dothammer/obwat2.jpg"><br /><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />754 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [2.56]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Dothammer&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>A related issue to the loot allocation problem.<br><br>Suppose your group of 4 or 5 are camping an area with known loot and you have already pre-decided who will get what.&nbsp;&nbsp;This happens alot in guild groups where most members do not care about loot and are mostly interested in XP.  <br><br>Suppose further someone outside the guild shows up and asks to join.  What should they expect? Should you have to re-do your loot scheme to accomodate the newcomer?  Should the newcomer expect any loot considerations?  Should the guild group just tell the newcomer 'sorry, cannot use you' even though the 'nice' thing to do would be to invite them?<br><br>For this example suppose the loot is valuable tradeskill items but not much reletive NPC value.<br><br>If I was the newcomer, I would tell the group up-front I do not expect any loot, I just want xp.  If they see fit to share anything, that is their choice.</p><br /><span class="sm">----------------------------</span><br />This place is a geographical oddity; It's two weeks from everywhere!</td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8"></td></tr></table>
