		   <table class="mform2"  border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform2" valign="top" id="forumSubject">
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Fri, Mar 4th 10:58 PM2005 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a class="sm" href="/forum.html?forum=1&mid=110832765395582215&num=73&page=2&post=1&replyto=110999532214281127"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=110999532214281127></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=1286"><span id=Encyclopedia>gbaji</span></a><b><span id=Encyclopedia><br>Encyclopedia</span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />9795 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Good [4.03]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=gbaji&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p><blockquote><b id="fs8">Dothammer wrote:</b><hr size="1" />Suppose your group of 4 or 5 are camping an area with known loot and you have already pre-decided who will get what.&nbsp;&nbsp;This happens alot in guild groups where most members do not care about loot and are mostly interested in XP.  <br><br>Suppose further someone outside the guild shows up and asks to join.  What should they expect? Should you have to re-do your loot scheme to accomodate the newcomer?  Should the newcomer expect any loot considerations?  Should the guild group just tell the newcomer 'sorry, cannot use you' even though the 'nice' thing to do would be to invite them?<hr size="1" /></blockquote><br><br>Yeah. That can be an uncomfortable problem, but it's usually resolved with good communication. If I'm in a guild/friend group, and we're able to handle the camp, and we're there specifically to get specific people specific drops, then that's the rule. If someone wants to join us, or we allow someone to join us, while they certainly are helping out, they were not *required* for us to get whatever drops we got, and we'll make it clear before they join that &quot;items x and y are already allocated&quot;.<br><br>Make that *really* clear before inviting someone. I've actually seen situations where we've been idly hunting mobs for a rarish epic drop for someone in my guild, and someone else will come along, ask if they can join us in the killing (it's obvious they can't solo here), and then start asking if the exact item drops, can he have it?. Um... No. That's why we're here. If you want to get some exp with us, and a share of the rest of the loot, you're welcome. But we're not here to get you your drop. We're here to get our guy his drop.<br><br>It can be a little bit uncomfortable, but if you're very upfront with it, most people will not have a problem with it. The only situation where it gets a bit annoying is when they ask if we'll stick around to get him his drop as well. That's kinda iffy, and depends on the rarity of the drop (and I suppose the quality of the exp and other loot that drops there). In many cases, the places you go to get specific drops may not be places you'd go normally for exp. Certainly, if we're shard camping for cleric clickies, there's no way in hell you could pay me enough to hunt in that crappy-ass zone except to help our guys get clickies. And the drop rate aint fast enough for us to sit around and collect an entire set for someone who just wandered by and asked. But if we're sitting in NC camping a particular named for a particular set of drops, and the exp is decent and we're all comfy, there's no reason we wont stick around and see if we can get more for someone who joined in and helped out.<br><br><br>Ultimately, what goes around comes around. You need to assess the value of helping out someone versus the value of your own time and effort. Make no mistake, in the situation you listed, that 6th guy isn't helping you, you are helping him. He's getting exp he would otherwise not be getting, and presumably some amount of loot he'd not otherwise be getting. Expecting to get a specific rare drop is a bit much. You may choose to do so if you want, but don't ever forget that in that situation you are doing him a favor. You're not just giving him his fair share. A &quot;fair share&quot; would be him not being in your group in the first place. Everything he got in addition to that is a gift from your group to his.<br><br>In most cases, it comes down to an assessment of the player. It's usually pretty quick and easy to determine the whiny-greedy folks from the nice-helpful folks. If I enjoy having someone in my group, then I see no reason not to keep hunting with that person (and potentially getting them the drop they are looking for). Heck. This is *especially* true for those difficult to get drops that some poor guy in a lower level guild may just not possibly be able to get otherwise. How nice a person he is will have a *huge* effect on our willingness to help out.<br><br><br>IMO, it's always a judgement call. I think you *can* help that person if you want, but in that situation, you are under absolutely no obligation to.</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from San Diego, CA</td></tr></table>
